=========================================
🔥 FUNCTORS (C++11) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is a Functor?
----------------------
A functor (function object) is a class or struct that overloads operator(),
so its objects can be called like functions.

👉 Object behaves like a function

-----------------------------------------

2. Basic Example
----------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Add {
public:
    int operator()(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
};

int main() {
    Add add;
    cout << add(2, 3);   // function-like call
}

Output:
5

-----------------------------------------

3. Why use Functors?
---------------------

Advantages:
✓ Can store state (data members)
✓ Can be used in STL algorithms
✓ More flexible than function pointers
✓ Can behave differently per object

-----------------------------------------

4. Functor with State
----------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Multiply {
    int factor;

public:
    Multiply(int f) : factor(f) {}

    int operator()(int x) {
        return x * factor;
    }
};

int main() {
    Multiply mul3(3);
    cout << mul3(10);   // 30
}

-----------------------------------------

5. Functor in STL (Custom Comparator)
--------------------------------------

#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

struct Compare {
    bool operator()(int a, int b) {
        return a > b;   // descending order
    }
};

int main() {
    vector<int> v = {3, 1, 4, 2};

    sort(v.begin(), v.end(), Compare());

    for (int x : v)
        cout << x << " ";
}

Output:
4 3 2 1

-----------------------------------------

6. C++11 Improvement (Lambda replaces functors)
-----------------------------------------------

sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int a, int b) {
    return a > b;
});

👉 Lambda = anonymous functor

-----------------------------------------

7. std::function (C++11)
-------------------------

#include <functional>
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    function<int(int,int)> f;

    f = [](int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    };

    cout << f(5, 6);
}

-----------------------------------------

8. Functor vs Function vs Lambda
---------------------------------

Feature      Function   Functor   Lambda
-----------------------------------------
State        ❌         ✔         ✔
Inline       ❌         ❌         ✔
Object       ❌         ✔         ✔
STL use      ✔         ✔         ✔

-----------------------------------------

